1
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:56,400
Hey, baby, what's going on here?

2
00:02:56,400 --> 00:02:57,800
Oh, hi.

3
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:19,900
Miss Gorightly!

4
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:25,000
Some day... Some day...!

5
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:26,700
Miss Gorightly!

6
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:33,200
You go to the powder room
and that's the last I see.

7
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:36,400
- Now, Harry...
- Harry was the other guy.

8
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:39,000
I'm Sid Arbuck.
You like me, remember?

9
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,400
Miss Gorightly! I protest!

10
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:45,800
Darling, I am sorry,
but I lost my key.

11
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:47,600
That was two weeks ago.

12
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:50,200
You cannot keep ringing my bell.

13
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:53,600
You disturb me!
You must have a key made!

14
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:55,800
But I just lose them all.

15
00:03:55,800 --> 00:03:59,600
- Come on. You like me.
- I worship you, Mr Arbuck.

16
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:02,300
- Good night.
- Wait! What is this?

17
00:04:02,300 --> 00:04:04,800
You like me. I'm a liked guy.

18
00:04:04,800 --> 00:04:08,000
You like me. I picked up
the cheque for five people...

19
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,500
Your friends.

20
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:13,300
When you wanted change for
the powder room I gave you $50.

21
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:15,000
That gives me rights.

22
00:04:15,100 --> 00:04:18,400
In 30 seconds I call the police!

23
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:20,600
All the time, disturbance!

24
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:22,100
I get no sleep!

25
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:24,900
I got to get my rest! I'm an artist!

26
00:04:24,900 --> 00:04:27,500
I going to call vice squad on you!

27
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:30,900
Don't be angry. I won't do it again.

28
00:04:30,900 --> 00:04:33,200
I might let you take those pictures.

29
00:04:34,900 --> 00:04:36,200
When?

30
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:37,900
Some time.

31
00:04:39,700 --> 00:04:41,600
Any time.

32
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:43,000
Good night.

33
00:06:03,800 --> 00:06:08,300
I'm sorry to bother you.
I couldn't get the door open.

34
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:13,100
I guess they sent me
the upstairs key.

35
00:06:13,100 --> 00:06:15,500
I couldn't get the
downstairs door open.

36
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:21,500
I said, I guess they sent me
the...upstairs key.

37
00:06:21,500 --> 00:06:25,400
I couldn't get the downstairs
door open. Sorry to wake you.

38
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:26,600
That's all right.

39
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:30,800
It could happen to anyone...
frequently does. Good night.

40
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:32,100
I hate to...

41
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
I hate to bother you,
but could I use the phone?

42
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:41,800
Sure.

43
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:43,800
Why not?

44
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:45,800
Thank you.

45
00:06:45,800 --> 00:06:47,800
Well, this is a...

46
00:06:47,800 --> 00:06:51,100
nice little place you've got here.

47
00:06:51,100 --> 00:06:53,600
You just moved in, too, huh?

48
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:55,900
I've been here about a year.

49
00:06:55,900 --> 00:06:58,300
Phone's over there.

50
00:06:58,300 --> 00:06:59,500
Well, it was.

51
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,600
Oh, I remember.

52
00:07:02,600 --> 00:07:06,400
I stuck it in the suitcase
to muffle the sound.

53
00:07:12,700 --> 00:07:15,000
I'm...sorry.

54
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:16,500
Is he all right?

55
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:19,400
Sure. He's OK, aren't you, cat?

56
00:07:19,400 --> 00:07:21,800
Poor old cat.

57
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:25,200
Poor slob. Poor slob without a name.

58
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:28,100
I don't have the right
to give him one.

59
00:07:28,100 --> 00:07:31,700
We don't own each other.
We just met one day.

60
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:33,600
I won't own anything

61
00:07:33,600 --> 00:07:36,800
until I find a place where
me and things go together.

62
00:07:36,800 --> 00:07:40,200
I'm not sure where that is,
but I know what it's like.

63
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:42,800
It's like Tiffany's.

64
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:45,400
Tiffany's?
You mean the jewellery store?

65
00:07:45,400 --> 00:07:47,200
That's right.

66
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:50,100
I'm crazy about Tiffany's.

67
00:07:50,100 --> 00:07:51,500
Listen.

68
00:07:51,500 --> 00:07:55,300
You know those days
when you get the mean reds?

69
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:58,700
The mean reds? You mean the blues?

70
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:04,500
The blues are when you're fat
or it's raining, that's all.

71
00:08:04,500 --> 00:08:06,400
The mean reds are horrible.

72
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:10,300
Suddenly, you're afraid
and don't know what of.

73
00:08:10,300 --> 00:08:13,200
- Do you ever get that feeling?
- Sure.

74
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:16,000
When I get it, all that does any good

75
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,600
is to jump in a cab to Tiffany's.

76
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:20,800
Calms me down right away.

77
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:23,000
The quietness and proudness of it.

78
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:24,800
Nothing bad could happen there.

79
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:27,400
If I could find a real place

80
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:29,500
that made me feel
like Tiffany's, then...

81
00:08:30,300 --> 00:08:34,300
I'd buy some furniture
and give the cat a name.

82
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:38,600
I'm sorry. You wanted something.

83
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:40,400
The telephone.

84
00:08:40,400 --> 00:08:42,300
I was supposed to meet somebody.

85
00:08:42,300 --> 00:08:45,800
This is 10:00 Thursday morning?

86
00:08:45,800 --> 00:08:48,700
I just got off a plane.
I'm not sure.

87
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:51,600
Thursday. Is this Thursday?

88
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,100
- I think so.
- It can't be!

89
00:08:54,100 --> 00:08:56,100
It's too gruesome!

90
00:08:58,100 --> 00:09:01,600
Well, what's so gruesome
about Thursday?

91
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:04,400
I never remember when it's coming up.

92
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:06,800
Wednesdays,
I generally don't go to bed

93
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:09,100
because I have to catch the 10:45.

94
00:09:09,100 --> 00:09:11,600
They're so particular
about visiting hours.

95
00:09:11,600 --> 00:09:14,400
Be a darling and look under the bed

96
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:16,700
for a pair of alligator shoes.

97
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:21,300
I've got to do something
about how I look.

98
00:09:21,300 --> 00:09:24,400
I can't go to Sing Sing
with a green face.

99
00:09:24,400 --> 00:09:27,500
Sing Sing?

100
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:30,200
It's a ridiculous name for a prison.

101
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:32,600
Sounds more like an opera house.

102
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:34,700
Black, alligator.

103
00:09:34,700 --> 00:09:39,000
All the visitors make an effort
to look their best.

104
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,500
It's touching, the women wearing
their prettiest things.

105
00:09:41,500 --> 00:09:45,600
I love them for it.
And I love the kids, too.

106
00:09:45,600 --> 00:09:48,500
It should be sad seeing kids
there, but it isn't.

107
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:53,300
They have ribbons in their hair
and shine on their shoes.

108
00:09:53,300 --> 00:09:54,700
As I understand it,

109
00:09:54,700 --> 00:09:57,400
you're going to visit somebody
at Sing Sing.

110
00:09:57,400 --> 00:10:01,000
You can tell what kind of person
a man thinks you are

111
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,000
by the earrings he gives you.

112
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
I must say, the mind reels.

113
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,700
- May I ask whom?
- Whom I'm going to visit?

114
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:10,600
I guess that's what I mean.

115
00:10:10,600 --> 00:10:12,800
I don't know if I should say.

116
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,000
They never told me not to.

117
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,200
Cross your heart and kiss your elbow.

118
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:19,200
I'll try.

119
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:21,600
You probably read about him -
Sally Tomato.

120
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:22,900
Sally Tomato?

121
00:10:22,900 --> 00:10:24,300
Don't look so shocked.

122
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:26,500
They couldn't prove
he was in the Mafia,

123
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:28,400
much less head of it.

124
00:10:28,400 --> 00:10:31,300
They only proved
he cheated his income tax.

125
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:33,400
He's a darling old man.

126
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:35,700
He wasn't my lover or anything.

127
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:39,000
I never knew him until
after he was in prison.

128
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:41,800
I've seen him every Thursday
for seven months.

129
00:10:41,800 --> 00:10:44,400
I'd go even if he didn't pay me.

130
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:47,500
- Shoes.
- I only found one.

131
00:10:50,100 --> 00:10:53,400
- He pays you?
- That's right. His lawyer does.

132
00:10:53,400 --> 00:10:56,100
If he is a lawyer, which I doubt.

133
00:10:56,100 --> 00:10:57,900
He only has an answering service

134
00:10:57,900 --> 00:11:00,600
and always wants to meet
at Hamburger Heaven.

135
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:04,600
There you are, you sneak. Thank you.

136
00:11:04,600 --> 00:11:06,100
You're welcome.

137
00:11:06,100 --> 00:11:08,400
Dress... Dress...

138
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:10,600
Here we are... Bag.

139
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:12,100
And a hat, too.

140
00:11:12,100 --> 00:11:13,400
There we are.

141
00:11:13,400 --> 00:11:16,500
Anyway, seven months ago,
this so-called lawyer

142
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:19,600
asked if I'd like
to cheer up an old man

143
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:22,100
and pick up 100 a week.

144
00:11:22,100 --> 00:11:25,400
I told him, "You've got
the wrong Holly Golightly."

145
00:11:25,400 --> 00:11:28,100
I do as well on trips
to the powder room.

146
00:11:28,100 --> 00:11:32,100
Any chic gentleman will give
a girl $50 for the powder room.

147
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:34,300
And cab fare, that's another 50.

148
00:11:34,300 --> 00:11:37,000
Then he said his client
was Sally Tomato.

149
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
Sally had seen me somewhere

150
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,200
and had admired me à la distance.

151
00:11:42,200 --> 00:11:45,100
It would be a good deed to visit him.

152
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:48,700
How could I say no?
It was so wildly romantic.

153
00:11:48,700 --> 00:11:50,800
How do I look?

154
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,200
Very good. I must say I'm amazed.

155
00:11:55,200 --> 00:11:57,800
I could never have
done it without you.

156
00:11:57,800 --> 00:11:59,200
Bag...

157
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:00,600
Call me any time.

158
00:12:01,700 --> 00:12:05,600
I'm just upstairs,
as soon as I get moved in.

159
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,100
Bye, cat.

160
00:12:11,800 --> 00:12:16,500
You mean he gives you $100
for an hour's conversation?

161
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:20,600
Mr O'Shaughnessy does when
I give him the weather report.

162
00:12:20,600 --> 00:12:24,700
It's none of my business,
but you could get in trouble.

163
00:12:24,700 --> 00:12:26,700
Hold this for me.

164
00:12:28,700 --> 00:12:31,500
And what do you mean,
weather report?

165
00:12:31,500 --> 00:12:34,000
Just a message
I give Mr O'Shaughnessy,

166
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,300
so he knows I've been there.

167
00:12:36,300 --> 00:12:39,200
Sally tells me things to say like...

168
00:12:39,200 --> 00:12:41,000
"There's a hurricane in Cuba",

169
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,000
"cloudy over Palermo",
things like that.

170
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,800
Don't worry. I've taken care
of myself for a long time.

171
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:56,300
Taxi!

172
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,100
- I never could do that.
- It's easy.

173
00:13:13,600 --> 00:13:15,300
Paul.

174
00:13:15,300 --> 00:13:18,700
I'm late. I know it.

175
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:23,700
Were you locked out?
Didn't you get the key?

176
00:13:23,700 --> 00:13:26,700
Oh, darling. I'm so sorry.

177
00:13:27,900 --> 00:13:29,700
No, I got the key.

178
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:33,200
Miss Golightly, my neighbour,
kindly let me in.

179
00:13:33,200 --> 00:13:36,000
Miss Golightly's
on her way to Sing Sing.

180
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:37,300
Just visiting, of course.

181
00:13:37,300 --> 00:13:38,600
Miss Golightly,

182
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:41,200
Mrs. Falenson, my...decorator.

183
00:13:41,200 --> 00:13:44,000
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

184
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,600
Darling. Let me look at you.

185
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:51,900
- Are you through?
- Was the flight ghastly?

186
00:13:51,900 --> 00:13:55,500
Grand Central station,
and step on it, darling.

187
00:13:56,800 --> 00:14:00,700
Is it only three weeks
since I left you in Rome?

188
00:14:00,700 --> 00:14:02,200
Seems like years.

189
00:14:02,200 --> 00:14:05,000
- You seen the apartment?
- Not yet.

190
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,800
It was wicked of me,
but I couldn't resist.

191
00:14:07,800 --> 00:14:10,000
I fixed it up without you.

192
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:11,500
I think it's darling,

193
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:16,700
but if you absolutely hate it,
we can start from scratch.

194
00:14:30,400 --> 00:14:32,800
Hey, baby! Where you going?

195
00:14:34,300 --> 00:14:37,700
Come on, baby. Open the door.

196
00:14:38,700 --> 00:14:40,500
Ah, be a pal!

197
00:14:41,600 --> 00:14:43,800
You're breaking up a beautiful party.

198
00:14:45,400 --> 00:14:48,300
Come on, baby. Open the door.

199
00:14:48,300 --> 00:14:51,200
Hey, the band's swinging.

200
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:53,900
Aw, come on, baby.

201
00:14:56,800 --> 00:14:59,800
Once again, I must protest!

202
00:14:59,800 --> 00:15:02,700
If you don't stop
that phonograph now,

203
00:15:02,700 --> 00:15:04,900
I'm going to call
the police department!

204
00:15:06,500 --> 00:15:09,500
Yeah. That's more better.

205
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:14,900
What's the matter, baby?

206
00:15:19,700 --> 00:15:23,100
Come on. You're a great kid.
Open the door.

207
00:15:25,100 --> 00:15:28,100
Come on, baby. I'm waiting for you.

208
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:29,000
- It's only me.
- Wait a minute. Miss...

209
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:31,100
Golightly. Holly Golightly.

210
00:16:31,100 --> 00:16:33,800
I live downstairs.
We met this morning, remember?

211
00:16:33,800 --> 00:16:35,300
Yeah.

212
00:16:36,400 --> 00:16:37,800
It's OK. She's gone.

213
00:16:39,300 --> 00:16:42,800
She works late hours for a decorator.

214
00:16:42,800 --> 00:16:45,300
There's the most
terrifying man downstairs.

215
00:16:45,300 --> 00:16:48,800
He's sweet when he isn't drunk,
but some vino,

216
00:16:48,800 --> 00:16:50,200
and, golly, quel beast.

217
00:16:50,200 --> 00:16:53,000
It got so tiresome,
I went out the window.

218
00:16:58,200 --> 00:17:01,000
You can throw me out if you want,

219
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:04,000
but you looked so cosy
and your friend had gone,

220
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,600
and it was getting cold out there.

221
00:17:07,800 --> 00:17:10,500
And I'd heard people in New York

222
00:17:10,500 --> 00:17:13,400
never get to know their neighbours.

223
00:17:13,400 --> 00:17:17,600
Well, how was Sing Sing?

224
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:20,800
Fine. I made the train
and everything.

225
00:17:21,800 --> 00:17:23,800
And what's the weather report?

226
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:25,600
Small-craft warnings,

227
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:28,700
Block Island to Hatteras...
whatever that means.

228
00:17:31,700 --> 00:17:35,000
You know, you're sweet.
You really are.

229
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:38,300
And you look a little
like my brother Fred.

230
00:17:38,300 --> 00:17:40,700
Do you mind if I call you Fred?

231
00:17:40,700 --> 00:17:42,100
Not at all.

232
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:49,600
300. She's very generous.

233
00:17:50,300 --> 00:17:52,900
Is it by the week, hour or what?

234
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:54,400
The party's over. Out.

235
00:17:54,400 --> 00:17:57,600
Oh, Fred. Darling Fred, I'm sorry.

236
00:17:57,600 --> 00:18:01,800
I didn't mean to hurt
your feelings. Don't be angry.

237
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:04,400
I was just saying I understand.

238
00:18:04,400 --> 00:18:06,900
I understand completely.

239
00:18:06,900 --> 00:18:09,500
Stick around. Make yourself a drink.

240
00:18:09,500 --> 00:18:11,800
- Throw me my robe.
- Stay where you are.

241
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:14,500
You must be absolutely exhausted.

242
00:18:14,500 --> 00:18:16,000
I mean, it's late,

243
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:18,900
and you were sound asleep
and everything.

244
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:23,700
I suppose you think
I'm très fou or something.

245
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:25,600
No fouer than anybody else.

246
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:28,500
Yes, you do. Everybody does.
I don't mind.

247
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:31,700
It's useful being top banana
in the shock department.

248
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:36,500
What do you do, anyway?

249
00:18:36,500 --> 00:18:41,200
- I'm a writer, I guess.
- You guess? Don't you know?

250
00:18:41,200 --> 00:18:44,200
OK. Positive statement.
Ringing affirmative.

251
00:18:44,200 --> 00:18:46,100
I'm a writer.

252
00:18:46,700 --> 00:18:50,600
The only writer I've ever been
out with is Benny Shacklett.

253
00:18:50,600 --> 00:18:54,800
He's written a lot of TV stuff,
but quel rat.

254
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:57,200
Tell me, are you a real writer?

255
00:18:57,200 --> 00:19:01,300
I mean, does anybody buy
what you write or anything?

256
00:19:01,300 --> 00:19:03,400
They bought what's in that box.

257
00:19:05,500 --> 00:19:06,600
Yours?

258
00:19:07,800 --> 00:19:09,200
All these books?

259
00:19:09,200 --> 00:19:11,100
There's just the one book,

260
00:19:11,100 --> 00:19:12,600
12 copies of it.

261
00:19:12,600 --> 00:19:16,200
"Nine Lives" by Paul Varjak.

262
00:19:16,200 --> 00:19:17,500
They're stories.

263
00:19:18,200 --> 00:19:19,500
Nine of them.

264
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:22,200
Tell me one.

265
00:19:23,200 --> 00:19:25,600
They're not the kind you can tell.

266
00:19:25,600 --> 00:19:27,800
Too dirty?

267
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:31,100
Yeah, I suppose they're dirty, too,

268
00:19:31,100 --> 00:19:32,900
but only incidentally.

269
00:19:32,900 --> 00:19:37,600
Mainly they're angry,
sensitive, intensely felt,

270
00:19:37,600 --> 00:19:40,900
and that dirtiest
of all words - promising.

271
00:19:40,900 --> 00:19:45,000
So said The Times Book Review,
October 1, 1956.

272
00:19:45,700 --> 00:19:48,200
- 1956?
- That's right.

273
00:19:48,900 --> 00:19:52,700
This a ratty question, but what
have you written lately?

274
00:19:53,800 --> 00:19:56,600
Lately, I've been working on a novel.

275
00:19:56,600 --> 00:19:59,700
- Lately, since 1956?
- It takes time.

276
00:19:59,700 --> 00:20:04,300
- I want to get it right.
- So no more stories.

277
00:20:04,300 --> 00:20:08,200
I'm supposed to not fritter
my talent on little things.

278
00:20:08,200 --> 00:20:10,900
I'm saving it for the big one.

279
00:20:10,900 --> 00:20:13,100
Do you write every day?

280
00:20:13,100 --> 00:20:14,400
Sure.

281
00:20:14,400 --> 00:20:16,900
- Today?
- Sure.

282
00:20:16,900 --> 00:20:19,200
It's a beautiful typewriter.

283
00:20:19,200 --> 00:20:20,200
Of course.

284
00:20:20,200 --> 00:20:23,300
It writes nothing but sensitive,
intensely felt, promising prose.

285
00:20:23,300 --> 00:20:24,800
There's no ribbon in it.

286
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:26,700
There isn't?

287
00:20:26,700 --> 00:20:28,900
No.

288
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:37,400
Something you said this morning
has bothered me all day.

289
00:20:37,400 --> 00:20:39,000
What's that?

290
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,300
Do they really give you $50
for the powder room?

291
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:44,100
Of course.

292
00:20:44,100 --> 00:20:46,400
You must do very well.

293
00:20:46,400 --> 00:20:50,600
I'm trying to save,
but I'm not very good at it.

294
00:20:54,600 --> 00:20:57,900
You know, you do look
a lot like my brother Fred.

295
00:20:57,900 --> 00:21:02,300
I haven't seen him since
I was 14, when I left home.

296
00:21:02,300 --> 00:21:05,800
He was already 6'2".

297
00:21:05,800 --> 00:21:08,900
It must have been
the peanut butter that did it.

298
00:21:08,900 --> 00:21:13,000
Everybody thought he was dotty,
the way he ate peanut butter.

299
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,700
But he wasn't dotty,

300
00:21:15,700 --> 00:21:19,700
just sweet and vague
and...terribly slow.

301
00:21:21,500 --> 00:21:25,900
Poor Fred. He's in the army now.

302
00:21:25,900 --> 00:21:28,400
It's best until I get enough money.

303
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:33,800
- And then?
- And then Fred and I...

304
00:21:33,800 --> 00:21:36,700
I went to Mexico once.

305
00:21:36,700 --> 00:21:40,000
It's a wonderful place
for raising horses.

306
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:44,100
I saw one place near the sea that...

307
00:21:44,100 --> 00:21:46,800
Fred's very good with horses.

308
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:49,800
Even land in Mexico costs something.

309
00:21:49,800 --> 00:21:55,000
Whatever I do, there's never
more than $200 in the bank.

310
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:57,000
It can't be 4:30.

311
00:21:58,400 --> 00:22:00,500
It just can't.

312
00:22:04,100 --> 00:22:08,300
Do you mind if I just
get in with you for a minute?

313
00:22:10,200 --> 00:22:13,100
It's all right. Really, it is.

314
00:22:13,100 --> 00:22:15,500
We're friends, that's all.

315
00:22:18,500 --> 00:22:21,000
We are friends, aren't we?

316
00:22:21,900 --> 00:22:23,200
Sure.

317
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,500
OK, let's don't say another word.

318
00:22:35,500 --> 00:22:37,900
Let's just go to sleep.

319
00:22:59,300 --> 00:23:00,800
Where are you, Fred?

320
00:23:03,700 --> 00:23:05,100
It's cold.

321
00:23:07,900 --> 00:23:11,900
There's snow and...wind.

322
00:23:13,500 --> 00:23:14,900
What is it?

323
00:23:19,400 --> 00:23:20,800
Why are you crying?

324
00:23:27,200 --> 00:23:31,400
If we're going to be friends,
let's get one thing straight.

325
00:23:31,400 --> 00:23:33,400
I hate snoops.

326
00:24:21,700 --> 00:24:24,700
- Yeah.
- Lucille, darling?

327
00:24:26,300 --> 00:24:28,900
I've been trying
desperately to reach you.

328
00:24:28,900 --> 00:24:30,800
Bill just got back...

329
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:32,600
a day early, the beast...

330
00:24:32,600 --> 00:24:35,000
so I'll have to beg off.

331
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:38,100
You'll explain
to the rest of the girls?

332
00:24:38,100 --> 00:24:39,900
You're a darling.

333
00:24:39,900 --> 00:24:43,400
Maybe we can have
a long lunch tomorrow.

334
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:47,700
- I'll phone you in the morning.
- Whatever you say.

335
00:24:47,700 --> 00:24:50,500
You'll manage to survive
without me tonight?

336
00:24:50,500 --> 00:24:55,300
Sure. I might even take a wild,
boyish fling at writing.

337
00:24:55,800 --> 00:24:58,800
- Good night.
- Good night.

338
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:25,000
Got yourself stuffed,
huh, Polly, baby?

339
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:26,900
Serves you right, big mouth.

340
00:25:32,200 --> 00:25:35,000
- Buon giorno.
- Huh?

341
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:36,900
Aren't you drinking?

342
00:25:39,200 --> 00:25:43,900
You have pockets or something?
What do you go by?

343
00:25:43,900 --> 00:25:46,700
What's your name?
What do you call yourself?

344
00:25:46,700 --> 00:25:50,000
- Irving.
- Perfect, perfect.

345
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:51,500
That's wonderful, Irving.

346
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:55,700
I'll be right back, Irving, baby.

347
00:26:02,100 --> 00:26:04,800
Yeah? Kid's still in the shower.
You expected?

348
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:07,100
I was invited. That what you mean?

349
00:26:07,100 --> 00:26:09,900
Don't get all tense. Come on in.

350
00:26:09,900 --> 00:26:12,700
It's a party - lot of characters
come who aren't expected.

351
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:15,000
I'll buy you a drink. You drink?

352
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:17,200
Then I'll buy you a drink.

353
00:26:18,200 --> 00:26:20,700
Hey, honey, your skirt's split there.

354
00:26:20,700 --> 00:26:23,200
- What do you drink?
- Bourbon.

355
00:26:23,200 --> 00:26:26,000
- On the rocks?
- Yeah... No. With water.

356
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:29,300
- Want rocks first?
- Yeah. Not too much.

357
00:26:29,300 --> 00:26:31,600
All right. That'll set you free.

358
00:26:31,600 --> 00:26:35,500
- Know the kid long?
- Not very. I live upstairs.

359
00:26:35,500 --> 00:26:39,300
Look at this place.
It's unbelievable. What a dump!

360
00:26:39,300 --> 00:26:40,800
What do you think?

361
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:43,100
- About what?
- Is she or isn't she?

362
00:26:44,200 --> 00:26:46,400
Wait a minute. Hold it.

363
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:50,200
- Harriet!
- Hi, JB.

364
00:26:50,200 --> 00:26:51,600
"JB"? What's that?

365
00:26:51,600 --> 00:26:54,400
- You know Gil.
- Yeah. How are you?

366
00:26:54,400 --> 00:26:57,800
- How about a drink?
- In the kitchen.

367
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:02,900
So... Oh, honey, that is you.

368
00:27:02,900 --> 00:27:05,500
Fred, darling,
I'm so glad you could come.

369
00:27:05,500 --> 00:27:08,200
I brought you a present
for the bookcase.

370
00:27:08,200 --> 00:27:10,900
You're sweet.

371
00:27:10,900 --> 00:27:13,800
Doesn't that look nice?
Give me a cigarette, OJ.

372
00:27:13,800 --> 00:27:17,600
OJ's a great agent.
He knows a lot of phone numbers.

373
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:19,600
What's Jerry Wald's phone number?

374
00:27:19,600 --> 00:27:21,100
Come on, lay off.

375
00:27:21,100 --> 00:27:24,000
Call him and tell him
Fred's a genius.

376
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,200
Stop blushing, Fred.
You didn't say it. I did.

377
00:27:27,200 --> 00:27:31,800
Quit stalling. How will you make
Fred rich and famous?

378
00:27:31,800 --> 00:27:34,600
Let Fred and me
settle that, huh, puppy?

379
00:27:34,600 --> 00:27:36,800
OK, but remember, I'm the agent.

380
00:27:36,800 --> 00:27:39,200
He's already got a decorator,
I'm the agent.

381
00:27:40,700 --> 00:27:42,100
Hold it.

382
00:27:42,100 --> 00:27:44,100
Hi, boys. Come on in.

383
00:27:44,100 --> 00:27:46,400
Everything you need's
in the kitchen.

384
00:27:48,600 --> 00:27:51,500
So, listen, Fred, baby...

385
00:27:51,500 --> 00:27:55,500
- No, it's Paul, baby.
- I thought it was Fred, baby.

386
00:27:55,500 --> 00:27:58,500
- Is she or isn't she?
- What?

387
00:27:58,500 --> 00:28:00,100
A phoney.

388
00:28:00,100 --> 00:28:03,000
I don't know. I don't think so.

389
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:05,800
Well, you're wrong - she is.

390
00:28:05,800 --> 00:28:10,600
On the other hand, you're right,
because she's a real phoney.

391
00:28:10,600 --> 00:28:13,600
She honestly believes
all this phoney junk.

392
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:16,200
Now, I sincerely
like the kid. I do.

393
00:28:16,200 --> 00:28:17,900
I'm sensitive. That's why.

394
00:28:17,900 --> 00:28:20,600
You got to be sensitive
to like the kid.

395
00:28:20,600 --> 00:28:22,900
It's a streak of the poet.

396
00:28:22,900 --> 00:28:24,400
You known her long?

397
00:28:24,400 --> 00:28:28,200
I discovered her. I'm OJ Berman.
Couple of years ago...

398
00:28:28,200 --> 00:28:31,000
She was just a kid.
Lot of style, class...

399
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:33,900
- Lot of what?
- Class.

400
00:28:33,900 --> 00:28:37,500
But you didn't know whether
she was a hillbilly or an Okie.

401
00:28:37,500 --> 00:28:40,300
Know how long it took
to smooth that accent?

402
00:28:40,300 --> 00:28:42,300
One year. Know how?

403
00:28:42,300 --> 00:28:44,200
We gave her French lessons.

404
00:28:44,200 --> 00:28:46,600
Figured once
she could imitate French,

405
00:28:46,600 --> 00:28:48,100
she could imitate English.

406
00:28:48,100 --> 00:28:51,000
Finally, I arranged
for a little screen test.

407
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,100
The night before - I could've
killed myself- the phone rings.

408
00:28:55,100 --> 00:29:00,200
I pick it up. She says, "It's
Holly. I'm in New York."

409
00:29:00,200 --> 00:29:03,500
I say, "You got
a screen test tomorrow."

410
00:29:03,500 --> 00:29:06,800
I say, "Get back here!"
She says, "I don't want to."

411
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:10,500
"What do you mean? What do you want?"

412
00:29:10,500 --> 00:29:14,000
She says, "When I find out,
I'll let you know."

413
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:16,500
- Fred, baby...
- It's Paul, baby.

414
00:29:16,500 --> 00:29:19,800
Sure. Don't tell me
she isn't a phoney.

415
00:29:19,800 --> 00:29:22,700
Irving!
Honey, Irving, where you been?

416
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:43,100
Mike, darling, I tried
reaching you all day long.

417
00:29:43,100 --> 00:29:45,000
Your answering service
doesn't answer.

418
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,800
That's the trouble
with answering services...

419
00:29:53,800 --> 00:29:56,100
And after all that she said...

420
00:30:06,900 --> 00:30:08,700
- Time, darling.
- What?

421
00:30:08,700 --> 00:30:09,700
The time?

422
00:30:09,700 --> 00:30:11,800
- You have a watch?
- No.

423
00:30:11,800 --> 00:30:14,500
- Oh, let me see. 6:45.
- Thank you.

424
00:30:25,600 --> 00:30:27,700
Really, was that necessary?

425
00:30:42,500 --> 00:30:46,400
This is some party. Who are
all these people, anyhow?

426
00:30:46,400 --> 00:30:48,700
Who knows? The word gets out.

427
00:30:48,700 --> 00:30:50,800
You don't mind, do you, darling?

428
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:53,200
Reinforcements.

429
00:30:57,800 --> 00:30:59,200
Right in there.

430
00:31:15,800 --> 00:31:18,100
Holly, darling!

431
00:31:18,100 --> 00:31:19,900
What's that?

432
00:31:19,900 --> 00:31:22,400
Mag Wildwood.

433
00:31:22,400 --> 00:31:26,300
She's a model, believe it
or not, and a thumping bore.

434
00:31:26,300 --> 00:31:28,700
But look at the goodies with her.

435
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:32,300
He's all right,

436
00:31:32,300 --> 00:31:34,700
if you like handsome,
rich-looking men

437
00:31:34,700 --> 00:31:37,000
with passionate natures
and too many teeth.

438
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:39,100
I mean the other one.

439
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:44,800
- The other one?
- He's Rusty Trawler.

440
00:31:47,300 --> 00:31:50,900
He's the ninth richest man
in America under 50.

441
00:31:52,400 --> 00:31:56,200
That's remarkable information
to have at your fingertips.

442
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:58,600
I keep track of these things.

443
00:31:58,600 --> 00:32:03,300
- Excuse me. You owe me 47...
- Hold this a minute, darling.

444
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:07,900
Mag, darling,
what are you doing here?

445
00:32:07,900 --> 00:32:10,400
I was upstairs
working with Yunioshi...

446
00:32:10,400 --> 00:32:12,600
Easter stuff for the Bazaar.

447
00:32:12,600 --> 00:32:16,500
Then these two nice boys
came to pick me up.

448
00:32:16,500 --> 00:32:19,900
It was a mistake, of course.
My wires got crossed somewhere.

449
00:32:19,900 --> 00:32:22,800
They were both very sweet about it.

450
00:32:22,800 --> 00:32:25,100
May I present Josè Silva Pereira?

451
00:32:25,100 --> 00:32:27,500
He's from Brazil.

452
00:32:27,600 --> 00:32:29,700
Miss Golightly.

453
00:32:30,900 --> 00:32:34,900
Very kind of you to allow me
to attend your party.

454
00:32:34,900 --> 00:32:38,000
I'm so interested
in North American culture.

455
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:40,900
I've been already
to the Statue of Liberty

456
00:32:40,900 --> 00:32:42,800
and to the restaurant Automatique,

457
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:45,300
but this is the first time

458
00:32:45,300 --> 00:32:48,200
I'm in a typical North American home.

459
00:32:48,200 --> 00:32:50,400
Wouldn't he just melt in your mouth?

460
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:52,200
And this is Mr Rusty Trawler.

461
00:32:52,200 --> 00:32:53,400
Miss Golightly.

462
00:32:53,400 --> 00:32:56,200
You're not vexed at me
for bringing them?

463
00:32:56,200 --> 00:32:58,700
- Of course not, darling.
- I'm glad.

464
00:32:58,700 --> 00:33:01,600
Now, who's going
to bring me a bourbon?

465
00:33:01,600 --> 00:33:03,700
- OJ.
- Yeah.

466
00:33:03,700 --> 00:33:05,800
Would you get Miss Wildwood a drink?

467
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:07,200
Which one's Miss Wildwood?

468
00:33:07,200 --> 00:33:10,200
Mr Berman, we haven't been
formally introduced,

469
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:14,100
but I'm Mag Wildwood
from Wildwood, Arkansaw.

470
00:33:14,100 --> 00:33:15,400
That's...hill country.

471
00:33:15,400 --> 00:33:18,300
Now, you just make yourself
right at home.

472
00:33:18,300 --> 00:33:19,800
Don't trouble yourself.

473
00:33:19,800 --> 00:33:23,100
I'm contented to observe
the customs of your country.

474
00:33:23,100 --> 00:33:24,600
OK, you do that.

475
00:33:24,600 --> 00:33:26,500
Now, come along, Mr Trawler.

476
00:33:26,500 --> 00:33:29,300
Let's see what we
can find to amuse you.

477
00:34:41,600 --> 00:34:43,400
I wasn't supposed to pick you up.

478
00:34:43,400 --> 00:34:44,900
At the last minute, I had...

479
00:34:44,900 --> 00:34:47,700
Look, I wasn't supposed
to pick you up.

480
00:34:51,200 --> 00:34:52,500
Yes?

481
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:56,200
Miss Gorightly!
This time I'm warning you!

482
00:34:56,200 --> 00:35:00,400
I am definitely this time
going to calling the police!

483
00:35:15,800 --> 00:35:18,300
Good evening!

484
00:35:18,300 --> 00:35:20,600
Is it something important?

485
00:35:20,600 --> 00:35:24,400
No. Just the guy upstairs
complaining about the noise.

486
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:25,800
He's angry.

487
00:35:25,800 --> 00:35:28,500
He did mention something
about calling the police.

488
00:35:28,500 --> 00:35:31,000
Oh, the police... The police?

489
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:34,600
That I cannot have. I'd better
find Miss Wildwood and go.

490
00:35:37,500 --> 00:35:40,400
To think I'd find a beau of mine

491
00:35:40,400 --> 00:35:43,300
mousing after
some cheap Hollywood trash.

492
00:35:43,300 --> 00:35:45,500
Mag, darling, you're being a bore.

493
00:35:45,500 --> 00:35:47,400
Shut up!

494
00:35:47,400 --> 00:35:50,700
You know what's going
to happen to you?

495
00:35:50,700 --> 00:35:56,200
I'm going to march you to the
zoo and feed you to the yak.

496
00:35:56,200 --> 00:35:58,900
Just as soon as I finish this drink.

497
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,500
Timber!

498
00:37:36,300 --> 00:37:38,300
Sorry.

499
00:37:39,800 --> 00:37:42,600
- Oh, good evening, Ed.
- It's Paul, baby.

500
00:37:42,600 --> 00:37:43,900
You remember Irving, don't you?

501
00:37:43,900 --> 00:37:48,000
- This is Josè.
- Nice to meet you.

502
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:49,300
Yes.

503
00:37:49,300 --> 00:37:50,800
Jewel thieves.

504
00:38:17,100 --> 00:38:19,200
Sally helps me with my accounts.

505
00:38:19,200 --> 00:38:21,900
I have no head for figures at all.

506
00:38:21,900 --> 00:38:24,600
I'm trying desperately
to save some money.

507
00:38:24,600 --> 00:38:26,400
I just can't seem to.

508
00:38:26,400 --> 00:38:29,200
He makes me write down everything.

509
00:38:29,200 --> 00:38:31,300
What I get, what I spend.

510
00:38:31,300 --> 00:38:34,700
I had an cheque account.
I got rid of that.

511
00:38:35,800 --> 00:38:40,800
He feels it's better to operate
on a cash basis, taxwise.

512
00:38:40,900 --> 00:38:45,600
Some day, take this book,
turn it into a novel.

513
00:38:45,600 --> 00:38:49,400
Everything is there.
Just fill in the details.

514
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:51,200
Would be good for some laughs.

515
00:38:51,200 --> 00:38:53,500
No. No, I don't think so.

516
00:38:53,500 --> 00:38:56,400
This book would break the heart.

517
00:38:56,400 --> 00:39:00,100
"Mr Fitzsimmons...powder room, $50.

518
00:39:00,100 --> 00:39:05,600
"Less $18... Repair
one black satin dress.

519
00:39:05,600 --> 00:39:07,800
"Cat food, 27 cents."

520
00:39:07,800 --> 00:39:11,800
Sally, darling, please stop -
you're making me blush!

521
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:15,100
But you're right about Jack.
He's an absolute rat.

522
00:39:15,100 --> 00:39:18,600
I guess, of course,
I don't know anybody but rats.

523
00:39:18,600 --> 00:39:20,900
Except, of course, Fred here.

524
00:39:22,200 --> 00:39:23,800
You do think Fred is nice, don't you?

525
00:39:23,800 --> 00:39:27,300
For you... I hope he is.

526
00:39:36,700 --> 00:39:40,500
Goodbye, Uncle Sally. Till next week.

527
00:39:40,500 --> 00:39:41,900
Goodbye, Uncle Sally.

528
00:39:41,900 --> 00:39:44,600
Goodbye and don't forget
to send that book.

529
00:39:44,600 --> 00:39:46,600
I won't.

530
00:39:46,600 --> 00:39:49,800
Oh, what about the weather report?

531
00:39:49,800 --> 00:39:50,800
Oh, yes.

532
00:39:50,800 --> 00:39:54,700
Snow flurries expected
this weekend in New Orleans.

533
00:39:57,800 --> 00:40:02,900
Snow flurries expected
this weekend in New Orleans?!

534
00:40:02,900 --> 00:40:04,700
Isn't that just the weirdest?

535
00:40:04,700 --> 00:40:08,600
I bet they haven't had
snow in New Orleans for years.

536
00:40:08,600 --> 00:40:11,200
I don't know how he thinks them up.

